  ["_base_blast_furnaces"] = {
    identifier = "_base_blast_furnaces",
    category_id = "_base_buildings",
    sidebar_text = "Blast Furnaces",
    page_type = "Global",
    paragraphs = {
      {
        paragraphType = "Header",
        header = "Blast Furnaces",
        text = "",
        image = nil,
        overrideMaxHeight = false,
        customMaxHeightPx = 0,
        addImageText = false,
        imageTextData = {},
      },
      {
        paragraphType = "Text",
        header = "",
        text = [[Blast furnaces provide a complex but highly efficient method to produce metallurgic goods.

To run a Blast Furnace you need three different types of modular buildings, an Air Intake, a Hot Air Stove and the Blast Furnace itself.

The outputs of a Blast Furnace are liquid (molten metal and molten slag) and need to be moved by pipes to casting/recycling machines.]],
        image = nil,
        overrideMaxHeight = false,
        customMaxHeightPx = 0,
        addImageText = false,
        imageTextData = {},
      },
      {
        paragraphType = "Text",
        header = "",
        text = [[The general concept of a blast furnace is to use a combination of extremely hot and pressurized air, fuel and mineral rock (which binds impurities) to melt impure ore or ingots into its purest (liquid) form. As a byproduct slag is created. Slag is generally a waste product but can be used in concrete production or be recycled.

The first building required is the Air Intake, which simply draws in air.]],
        image = nil,
        overrideMaxHeight = false,
        customMaxHeightPx = 0,
        addImageText = false,
        imageTextData = {},
      },
      {
        paragraphType = "Image",
        header = "",
        text = "",
        image = "Assets/FoundryAssets/UI/InfoDatabase_Images/infoDB_blastFurnace01.png|8d57f2d5ef727a544836ceca54835077",
        overrideMaxHeight = false,
        customMaxHeightPx = 0,
        addImageText = false,
        imageTextData = {},
      },
      {
        paragraphType = "Text",
        header = "",
        text = "The second building is the Hot Air Stove, a heating tower that heats up the air from the Air Intake. They can be run on power or on fuel items, this depends on the power module you chose when building it.",
        image = nil,
        overrideMaxHeight = false,
        customMaxHeightPx = 0,
        addImageText = false,
        imageTextData = {},
      },
      {
        paragraphType = "Image",
        header = "",
        text = "",
        image = "Assets/FoundryAssets/UI/InfoDatabase_Images/infoDB_blastFurnace02.png|30fc7b1282ed5764c83477cd4dab5eca",
        overrideMaxHeight = false,
        customMaxHeightPx = 0,
        addImageText = false,
        imageTextData = {},
      },
      {
        paragraphType = "Text",
        header = "",
        text = [[And finally the Blast Furnace which consumes the hot air, the fuel (Coked Ignium), the metal and the mineral rock.

Note: Due to the size of the buildings, pipelines are used instead of pipes to move the large amounts of air required. They work the same as pipes, but are bigger and have higher throughputs.]],
        image = nil,
        overrideMaxHeight = false,
        customMaxHeightPx = 0,
        addImageText = false,
        imageTextData = {},
      },
      {
        paragraphType = "Image",
        header = "",
        text = "",
        image = "Assets/FoundryAssets/UI/InfoDatabase_Images/infoDB_blastFurnace03.png|009e815c66e93a942a478f278190a126",
        overrideMaxHeight = false,
        customMaxHeightPx = 0,
        addImageText = false,
        imageTextData = {},
      },
      {
        paragraphType = "Header",
        header = "Unique Mechanics",
        text = "",
        image = nil,
        overrideMaxHeight = false,
        customMaxHeightPx = 0,
        addImageText = false,
        imageTextData = {},
      },
      {
        paragraphType = "Text",
        header = "",
        text = [[Blast Furnaces are more complex than regular machines in their basic behavior.

<b><u>Temperature:</u></b> Blast Furnaces do not operate instantly once activated, they require to be heated up first. This may take a while. Failing to provide enough hot air will cool them down again.

<b><u>Fill Rate and Content:</u></b> Blast Furnaces have an indicator how full they are, they need to be filled to a certain threshold before they can operate. But you should fill them up as much as possible, see next paragraph.

<b><u>Efficiency:</u></b> A Blast Furnace operates most cost-efficiently when it is constantly producing and when it is filled as much as possible. You should ensure that there is more or equal ore than the Blast Furnaces consumption rate is, otherwise you will waste hot air (which is infinite, but it'll cost more power to heat larger quantities). Similarily you'll waste hot air when the Blast Furnace is overproducing and backing up.
Note: This mechanic provides a bit of an extra challenge if you want to optimize, but it's not too punishing in case you do not use it in an optimal way. 

<b><u>Insufficient Hot Air:</u></b> Blast Furnaces need a steady supply of hot air to stay heated (they require less hot air the fuller they are). If you're unable (for example because of a power shortage) to provide them with enough hot air to heat up or stay heated, you are wasting the hot air. Imagine it like that: If the Blast Furnace needs a certain amount of hot air per second to heat up and you only deliver half of it, all the hot air is just wasted. In this case it is better to shut everything down and fix the hot air supply first.

<b><u>Dismantle/Modify:</u></b> Once started the Blast Furnace cannot be demolished until it is shut down again. Blast Furnaces convert all their content to slag when shut down and they need to be emptied first before you can dismantle or modify them.]],
        image = nil,
        overrideMaxHeight = false,
        customMaxHeightPx = 0,
        addImageText = false,
        imageTextData = {},
      },
    },
  },
  ["_base_boiler_and_turbine"] = {
    identifier = "_base_boiler_and_turbine",
    category_id = "_base_buildings",
    sidebar_text = "Boiler & Turbine",
    page_type = "PerCharacter",
    paragraphs = {
      {
        paragraphType = "Header",
        header = "Boiler & Turbine Setup",
        text = "",
        image = nil,
        overrideMaxHeight = false,
        customMaxHeightPx = 0,
        addImageText = false,
        imageTextData = {},
      },
      {
        paragraphType = "Text",
        header = "",
        text = [[Boilers and Turbines can be used to create power more efficiently, but it requires a more complex setup.

First you need a Pipe Intake at a water source to draw in water.

As second step the water needs to be moved to the Boiler, which will convert it into steam as soon as it is supplied with burnable items.

Finally the steam goes to the Turbine, which generates High-Voltage-Power (HVP).]],
        image = nil,
        overrideMaxHeight = false,
        customMaxHeightPx = 0,
        addImageText = false,
        imageTextData = {},
      },
      {
        paragraphType = "Image",
        header = "",
        text = "",
        image = "Assets/FoundryAssets/UI/InfoDatabase_Images/infoDB_BoilerAndTurbine.jpg|5dfc405729af9f94eb3e44ac0a98577c",
        overrideMaxHeight = false,
        customMaxHeightPx = 0,
        addImageText = false,
        imageTextData = {},
      },
    },
  },
  ["_base_burner_generator"] = {
    identifier = "_base_burner_generator",
    category_id = "_base_buildings",
    sidebar_text = "Burner Generator",
    page_type = "PerCharacter",
    paragraphs = {
      {
        paragraphType = "Header",
        header = "Burner Generator",
        text = "",
        image = nil,
        overrideMaxHeight = false,
        customMaxHeightPx = 0,
        addImageText = false,
        imageTextData = {},
      },
      {
        paragraphType = "Text",
        header = "",
        text = "The Burner Generator produces low-voltage-power and powers the Building Blocks it's built on top. It consumes burnable items (items with a \"fuel value\" in their tooltip, e.g. Ignium Ore or Biomass) in order to produce energy.",
        image = nil,
        overrideMaxHeight = false,
        customMaxHeightPx = 0,
        addImageText = false,
        imageTextData = {},
      },
      {
        paragraphType = "Image",
        header = "",
        text = "",
        image = "Assets/FoundryAssets/UI/InfoDatabase_Images/infoDB_burnerGenerator.jpg|e996b87543b2cf4468b6c19af1571829",
        overrideMaxHeight = false,
        customMaxHeightPx = 0,
        addImageText = false,
        imageTextData = {},
      },
      {
        paragraphType = "Text",
        header = "",
        text = "It is recommended to use Ignium Ore (red ore) over Biomass as fuel since it has a higher fuel value and the mining process can be automated.",
        image = nil,
        overrideMaxHeight = false,
        customMaxHeightPx = 0,
        addImageText = false,
        imageTextData = {},
      },
    },
  },
  ["_base_cargo_ships"] = {
    identifier = "_base_cargo_ships",
    category_id = "_base_buildings",
    sidebar_text = "Cargo Shuttles",
    page_type = "Global",
    paragraphs = {
      {
        paragraphType = "Header",
        header = "Cargo Shuttles",
        text = "",
        image = nil,
        overrideMaxHeight = false,
        customMaxHeightPx = 0,
        addImageText = false,
        imageTextData = {},
      },
      {
        paragraphType = "Text",
        header = "",
        text = [[Cargo shuttles and their landing pads provide a straight-forward way for transporting goods over long distances on the planet. They cannot reach the space station.

There are two types of landing pads: The start pad and the target pad. Each start pad has its own cargo shuttle and will move items to a target pad of your choice.]],
        image = nil,
        overrideMaxHeight = false,
        customMaxHeightPx = 0,
        addImageText = false,
        imageTextData = {},
      },
      {
        paragraphType = "Image",
        header = "",
        text = "",
        image = "Assets/FoundryAssets/UI/InfoDatabase_Images/infoDB_cargoShips01.png|7466df39bad08c143b300fa4eed24e07",
        overrideMaxHeight = false,
        customMaxHeightPx = 0,
        addImageText = false,
        imageTextData = {},
      },
      {
        paragraphType = "Header",
        header = "Basic Configuration",
        text = "",
        image = nil,
        overrideMaxHeight = false,
        customMaxHeightPx = 0,
        addImageText = false,
        imageTextData = {},
      },
      {
        paragraphType = "Text",
        header = "",
        text = [[To set up an automated transportation route you should start with choosing a name for your target pad, it can be configured on its screen panel.

The next step is to set the name of the target pad as destination on the start pad, that tells the cargo ship where to fly to.

You can achieve additional control over the behavior by configuring the take-off conditions, telling the cargo ship when it is allowed to take off.]],
        image = nil,
        overrideMaxHeight = false,
        customMaxHeightPx = 0,
        addImageText = false,
        imageTextData = {},
      },
      {
        paragraphType = "Image",
        header = "",
        text = "",
        image = "Assets/FoundryAssets/UI/InfoDatabase_Images/infoDB_cargoShips02.png|c25beb3dad2fa254b9a70882e94800e4",
        overrideMaxHeight = false,
        customMaxHeightPx = 0,
        addImageText = false,
        imageTextData = {},
      },
      {
        paragraphType = "Header",
        header = "Take-Off Conditions",
        text = "",
        image = nil,
        overrideMaxHeight = false,
        customMaxHeightPx = 0,
        addImageText = false,
        imageTextData = {},
      },
      {
        paragraphType = "Text",
        header = "",
        text = [[There are two possible conditions:
<b>Inventory Fill Percentage:</b> How full the cargo inventory is, 100% means it's filled to the maximum.
<b>Time passed:</b> Seconds passed since how long the ship is docked.

You can choose to enable either one or both conditions. If you enable both you can additionally tell the shuttle if both conditions need to be fulfilled (select "AND" button) or if the first that activates should make the shuttle start its flight (select "OR" button).]],
        image = nil,
        overrideMaxHeight = false,
        customMaxHeightPx = 0,
        addImageText = false,
        imageTextData = {},
      },
      {
        paragraphType = "Image",
        header = "",
        text = "",
        image = "Assets/FoundryAssets/UI/InfoDatabase_Images/infoDB_cargoShips03.png|51deac53415de504698bd16a5a2d8730",
        overrideMaxHeight = false,
        customMaxHeightPx = 0,
        addImageText = false,
        imageTextData = {},
      },
      {
        paragraphType = "Header",
        header = "In-depth mechanics",
        text = "",
        image = nil,
        overrideMaxHeight = false,
        customMaxHeightPx = 0,
        addImageText = false,
        imageTextData = {},
      },
      {
        paragraphType = "Text",
        header = "",
        text = [[Cargo shuttles will leave the start pad once the start condition has been fulfilled. If multiple shuttles are on their way to the target pad, they will form a queue in the sky and land after each other. The queue is based on order of take off. In case of many shuttles going to the same pad you might want to consider placing a second target pad, see next paragraph.

Multiple target pads can have the same name, in such case the cargo shuttle will pick the closest available target pad on take-off. If you need a higher throughput, build multiple landing pads with the same name and multiple start pads with the same target.

Your cargo shuttles can only be loaded while they are docked, to speed things up it's adviseable to buffer items next to your start pad and have multiple conveyors feed the cargo shuttle as soon as it docks.]],
        image = nil,
        overrideMaxHeight = false,
        customMaxHeightPx = 0,
        addImageText = false,
        imageTextData = {},
      },
    },
  },
  ["_base_character_customization"] = {
    identifier = "_base_character_customization",
    category_id = "_base_general",
    sidebar_text = "Character Customization",
    page_type = "Global",
    paragraphs = {
      {
        paragraphType = "Header",
        header = "Character Customization",
        text = "",
        image = nil,
        overrideMaxHeight = false,
        customMaxHeightPx = 0,
        addImageText = false,
        imageTextData = {},
      },
      {
        paragraphType = "Text",
        header = "",
        text = "You can customize your character's appearance with different looks and colors. To do so, visit the door of your drop pod on the opposite side of the smelters.",
        image = nil,
        overrideMaxHeight = false,
        customMaxHeightPx = 0,
        addImageText = false,
        imageTextData = {},
      },
      {
        paragraphType = "Image",
